# Fast-MCP conventions

Use **Fast-MCP** (`fastmcp`) as the MCP server framework. Single source of truth: [FastMCP Python SDK](https://gofastmcp.com/python-sdk/fastmcp-server-server).

## Tools

- Expose actions as `@mcp.tool` functions.
- Provide clear **docstrings** (they become tool descriptions for the LLM).
- Use **type hints** on all parameters and return types so the SDK can generate the JSON schema.

## Naming

- Tool names and parameters in `snake_case`.
- Keep tool names clear and action-oriented (e.g. `run_scan`, `list_insertion_points`).

## Inputs

For tools that take a "request" or "target," prefer structured inputs (e.g. Pydantic models or typed dicts) that map to the Request/InsertionPoint model in [docs/WebEndpoint_and_insertion_points_report.md](../docs/WebEndpoint_and_insertion_points_report.md). Avoid raw string blobs when structured input is feasible.

## Errors

- Raise meaningful exceptions; avoid swallowing errors.
- Do not expose stack traces or internal paths to the MCP client.

## Server layout

- One `FastMCP(name="...")` instance per logical server (webrecon, sqli, xss).
- Each server has its own entrypoint (e.g. `python -m servers.webrecon`).
- Use `add_provider()` or middleware if the project grows.
